ng is the most common type of testicular cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Yolk sac tumour","Choriocarcinoma","Seminoma","Teratoma","Embryonal carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeminoma\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common type of testicular cancer, accounting for approximately 40% of all testicular germ cell tumours. It typically presents in men aged 25-45 years and has an excellent prognosis with appropriate treatment.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EYolk sac tumours\u003C/strong\u003E are more common in children and comprise about 1% of adult testicular tumours. \u003Cstrong\u003EChoriocarcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare and aggressive form, representing less than 1% of testicular cancers. \u003Cstrong\u003ETeratoma\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for approximately 5-10% of testicular tumours and contains tissue from multiple germ layers. \u003Cstrong\u003EEmbryonal carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E represents about 20% of testicular cancers and tends to be more aggressive.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Seminoma is the most common type of testicular cancer, accounting for approximately 40% of all testicular germ cell tumours.","Testicular cancers are classified into seminomatous and non-seminomatous germ cell tumours."],"references":["Boccellino M, Vanacore D, Zappavigna S, Cavaliere C, Rossetti S, D\u0027Aniello C, Chieffi P, Amler E, Buonerba C, Di Lorenzo G, Di Franco R, Izzo A, Piscitelli R, Iovane G, Muto P, Botti G, Perdon\u00e0 S, Caraglia M, Facchini G. Testicular cancer from diagnosis to epigenetic factors. Oncotarget. 2017 Sep 18;8(61):104654-104663. doi: 10.18632/oncotarget.20992. PMID: 29262668; PMCID: PMC5732834.","Chung P, Warde P. Testicular cancer: germ cell tumours. BMJ Clin Evid. 2016 Jan 7;2016:1807. PMID: 26741128; PMCID: PMC4704678.","Cheng L, Albers P, Berney DM, Feldman DR, Daugaard G, Gilligan T, Looijenga LHJ. Testicular cancer. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2018 Oct 5;4(1):29. doi: 10.1038/s41572-018-0029-0. PMID: 30291251.","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48415"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15873"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48415"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T13:37:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T13:38:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8564"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62964"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for 